</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/stress-management-tips--the-mandatory-training-group-uk--1680775613703.png?v=1680775656" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/stress-management-tips--the-mandatory-training-group-uk--1680775613703.png?v=1680775656 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/t/33/assets/stress-management-tips--the-mandatory-training-group-uk--1680775613703_500x.png?v=1680775656 320w" width="3000" height="2250" alt="Stress management tips - The Mandatory Training Group UK - " title="Stress management tips - The Mandatory Training Group UK - " style="aspect-ratio:3000 / 2250" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-hmjpVf jFnkub pf-66_"/><p class="sc-gDGHff eHTxVX pf-67_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-eoHXOn hKPgxQ pf-69_">Whenever you feel stressed at work due to a heavy workload, it is vital to ensure that you do not attempt to accomplish everything at once or concentrate on things you cannot change. Instead, set small targets you can easily achieve. Focus your time and energy on helping yourself feel better.<br>
<br>Regular exercise can help burn off nervous energy. Positive thinking can also improve your health, so consider thinking about the good things in your life. Make a list of three things you are thankful for each day.<br>
<br>You can also think of friends or coworkers who have overcome difficulties and setbacks in the past and let them inspire you to deal with your current problems.<br>
<br>Additionally, avoid alcohol, cigarettes, gambling, or drugs to relieve stress. All of which can negatively impact your mental health.<br>
